	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Imaginary Friends</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sparrow">Sparrow</a></li><li><a href="/issues/461">May 2014</a></li></ul>

			</div>

																			

				<figure class="block-content-photo block-content-photo-large photo photo-outset-center-small">
					
					<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 1361 1960'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/681x980r/photos/461-22-margolis.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/1361x1960r/photos/461-22-margolis.jpg
	 alt="461 - Margolis - Sparrow"
	 class="lazy">

										<figcaption>

												<div class="photo-caption">
							<p><span class="smallcaps">Loretta Judson/Richard Margolis</span></p>
						</div>
						
																				<div class="photo-credit">
								&copy;&nbsp;<a href="/contributors/richard-margolis">Richard Margolis</a>
							</div>
																		</figcaption>
									</figure>

					</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><strong>A Democratic Theory Of God</strong><br />
God should be an elected position. The electorate should be presented with various images of God: purely loving; harsh and vengeful; indifferent, etc. Then every person on earth should vote. Whoever wins will be God for the next four years.</p>

<p><strong>Same-Sex</strong><br />
A same-sex marriage is one where the partners have the same sex, year after year: dull and routine.</p>

<p>Same-sex marriage is extremely common in the United States.</p>

<p><strong>Anomalous Dishes</strong><br />
When staying with friends, I make it a point to help put away dishes from the dishwasher or drying rack. Most of the items are easy to reshelve, but I always find an anomaly &mdash; a very small spoon, an oblong platter &mdash; and I must ask my host where it goes. I feel great affection for the single ceremonial fork, the lonely egg cup.</p>

<p><strong>Five Blind Men And A Camel</strong><br />
Five blind men met a camel. Each one touched a different part of the animal. Afterward all of them recognized it as a camel.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How did you know?&rdquo; someone asked.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It smelled like a camel,&rdquo; said the five blind men.</p>

<p><strong>A Dog In Brooklyn</strong><br />
While visiting Brooklyn, I heard a dog barking in a courtyard. One dog can annoy a thousand people, but one person can&rsquo;t annoy a thousand dogs.</p>

<p><strong>Redeeming A Desk</strong><br />
&ldquo;I bought a writing desk from a failed novelist,&rdquo; Ted told me. &ldquo;Now I write at it every day, trying to redeem the desk.&rdquo;</p>

<p><strong>Christian Humor</strong><br />
I see a woman in her forties carrying a cloth bag labeled &ldquo;FROG&rdquo; &mdash; with a cartoon image of a frog on it. Below it, in smaller print, is written: &ldquo;Fully Reliant On God.&rdquo; So there <em>is </em>Christian humor!</p>

<p><strong>Alternate Breathing</strong><br />
Try this with your husband or wife: On a warm summer night, sit together in the living room and breathe alternately. While you breathe in, your spouse breathes out, and vice versa.</p>

<p>Alternate breathing is better for a relationship than couples therapy.</p>

<p><strong>The Dangers Of Postal Warming</strong><br />
Post offices are definitely getting hotter. Each time I walk into the one in my town, I unzip my coat. I never had to do this two years ago.</p>

<p><strong>Types Of Atheism</strong><br />
Technically one must be an atheist of a particular religion. Jewish atheists, for example, reject the Old Testament God. Christian atheists deny the divinity of Christ. And atheist Hindus disbelieve in thousands of gods.</p>

<p><strong>Yo</strong><br />
&ldquo;Did you clean the sink?&rdquo; I ask my wife.</p>

<p>She says a word in response that is difficult to describe: a combination of <em>yes</em> and <em>no</em> that sounds something like <em>yo</em>. I ask her again, and she replies with the same word.</p>

<p>Somehow my wife has invented a word halfway between <em>yes </em>and <em>no</em>.</p>

<p><strong>Imaginary Friends</strong><br />
As a child I had imaginary friends. So did my daughter. Is it possible that my daughter&rsquo;s imaginary friends were the children of mine?</p>

<p><strong>Dogs</strong><br />
Dogs don&rsquo;t think they&rsquo;re dogs. They think they&rsquo;re cowboys.</p>

<p><strong>Obsolescence</strong><br />
&ldquo;There&rsquo;s nothing wrong with planned obsolescence!&rdquo; my electrician Rob told me. &ldquo;Leaves on trees are planned obsolescence.&rdquo;</p>

<p><strong>Poor And Rich</strong><br />
It&rsquo;s easy to become poor: just give away all your money, or burn it. But becoming rich is not so simple.</p>

<p><strong>Manifest Destiny</strong><br />
In the nineteenth century the United States had a Manifest Destiny &mdash; to expand across the continent. Today we have an Unfathomable Destiny.</p>

<p><strong>Single God</strong><br />
God never got married. He chose the career path.</p>

<p><strong>The Demise Of Cool</strong><br />
The word <em>cool</em> has come to mean the opposite of its original, true meaning.</p>

<p>The slang definition of <em>cool</em> was once connected to its literal definition: cold, aloof, uninvolved. When Miles Davis played Carnegie Hall, his back was to the audience. When they applauded wildly, he walked off the stage. Miles Davis was cool.</p>

<p>In Bob Dylan&rsquo;s &ldquo;Love Minus Zero/No Limit,&rdquo; the nameless heroine &ldquo;knows there&rsquo;s no success like failure / and that failure&rsquo;s no success at all.&rdquo; She was cool.</p>

<p>Today any achievement is greeted with the word <em>cool</em>.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Your track team won the semifinals? Cool!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You got a Lexus? Cool!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re going to Club Med? That&rsquo;s so cool!&rdquo;</p>

<p>When Alexander the Great reached the River Ganges, he met a yogi. &ldquo;I have conquered the world,&rdquo; explained Alexander. &ldquo;What can I do for you?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You can step out of my way,&rdquo; replied the ascetic. &ldquo;You&rsquo;re blocking my view of the sun.&rdquo;</p>

<p>That yogi was cool.</p>

<p>Today Alexander the Great would be told, &ldquo;You conquered India? Cool!&rdquo;</p>

<p><strong>Chocolate Water</strong><br />
I walked out of my house; next to my driveway was a puddle. The water was three inches deep and muddy, the color of milk chocolate. I wanted to splash in the puddle but decided I was too old.</p>

<p>I went back inside the house and filled the bathtub with hot water. Reclining in my warm, comforting bath, I thought, <em>I&rsquo;d rather be sitting in that puddle</em>.</p>

<p><strong>Taoist Monopoly</strong><br />
Today my daughter and I played Taoist Monopoly. We agreed to play for only twenty minutes; thus no one could win. We bought only properties we liked, not ones that were valuable. I noticed that I desired Baltic Avenue and Mediterranean Avenue, with their lovely deep-purple color and simple rents: $2 and $4. I refused to buy Boardwalk.</p>

<p>At the end of our game we were both in jail.</p>
														</div>


				
